<h2 id="chapter-3-finding-the-right-first-role">Chapter 3: Finding the Right First Role</h2>

<h3 id="green-flags-companies-that-invest-in-juniors">Green Flags: Companies That Invest in Juniors</h3>

<p><strong>What to look for:</strong></p>

<p><strong>1. Mentorship Structure</strong></p>
<ul>
  <li>Do they assign mentors to junior developers?</li>
  <li>Is mentoring part of senior developers‚Äô job expectations?</li>
  <li>Do they have a structured onboarding program?</li>
</ul>

<p><strong>2. Growth-Focused Culture</strong></p>
<ul>
  <li>Do they talk about learning and development in the job description?</li>
  <li>Is there a clear path from junior to mid-level?</li>
  <li>Do they invest in training and conferences?</li>
</ul>

<p><strong>3. Supportive Environment</strong></p>
<ul>
  <li>How do they talk about mistakes and learning?</li>
  <li>Is there psychological safety to ask questions?</li>
  <li>Do senior devs seem excited about mentoring?</li>
</ul>

<p><strong>4. Realistic Expectations</strong></p>
<ul>
  <li>Do they understand juniors need time to ramp up?</li>
  <li>Are timelines reasonable for someone learning?</li>
  <li>Is the role actually junior, or mid-level with junior pay?</li>
</ul>

<p><strong>Questions to ask in interviews:</strong></p>

<ul>
  <li>‚ÄúWhat does mentorship look like for junior developers here?‚Äù</li>
  <li>‚ÄúHow do senior developers feel about mentoring juniors?‚Äù</li>
  <li>‚ÄúWhat does success look like for a junior in the first 3/6/12 months?‚Äù</li>
  <li>‚ÄúCan you tell me about a time a junior developer struggled and how the team supported them?‚Äù</li>
  <li>‚ÄúWhat‚Äôs the worst thing about working here?‚Äù (See if they‚Äôre honest)</li>
</ul>

<h3 id="red-flags-companies-to-avoid">Red Flags: Companies to Avoid</h3>

<p><strong>Warning signs:</strong></p>

<p><strong>1. The ‚ÄúSelf-Starter‚Äù Trap</strong>
If they emphasize independence over support, they‚Äôre looking for a mid-level developer at junior pay.</p>

<p><strong>2. The Pressure Cooker</strong>
‚ÄúFast-paced environment‚Äù without mentorship structure = burnout central.</p>

<p><strong>3. The Swiss Army Knife</strong>
If they want you to be expert in 10+ technologies on day one, they don‚Äôt understand junior roles.</p>

<p><strong>4. The Dismissive Culture</strong>
If senior developers act annoyed by questions in interviews, imagine working there.</p>

<p><strong>5. The Impossible Timeline</strong>
‚ÄúWe need someone who can ship a feature in their first week‚Äù = unrealistic expectations.</p>

<h3 id="what-about-remote-vs-on-site">What About Remote vs. On-Site?</h3>

<p><strong>Remote advantages:</strong></p>
<ul>
  <li>Access to more opportunities (not limited by location)</li>
  <li>Flexibility for learning and balance</li>
  <li>Often more async communication (great for thoughtful responses)</li>
</ul>

<p><strong>Remote challenges:</strong></p>
<ul>
  <li>Harder to ask quick questions</li>
  <li>Less ambient learning from overhearing conversations</li>
  <li>Requires more intentional connection-building</li>
</ul>

<p><strong>Questions to ask about remote work:</strong></p>
<ul>
  <li>‚ÄúHow do you onboard remote junior developers?‚Äù</li>
  <li>‚ÄúWhat communication tools do you use?‚Äù</li>
  <li>‚ÄúHow do you handle mentorship remotely?‚Äù</li>
  <li>‚ÄúAre there regular video calls or mostly async?‚Äù</li>
  <li>‚ÄúHow do you build team connection remotely?‚Äù</li>
</ul>

<h3 id="salary-expectations">Salary Expectations</h3>

<p><strong>Be realistic but not undervalued:</strong></p>

<p>Research typical junior salaries in your area/role:</p>
<ul>
  <li>Use Glassdoor, levels.fyi, salary.com</li>
  <li>Ask in your community (many people share ranges)</li>
  <li>Consider cost of living adjustments for remote roles</li>
</ul>

<p><strong>Don‚Äôt undersell yourself:</strong>
Yes, you‚Äôre junior. But you‚Äôre also:</p>
<ul>
  <li>Bringing fresh perspectives</li>
  <li>Eager to learn and contribute</li>
  <li>Solving real business problems</li>
</ul>

<p>If they‚Äôre paying significantly below market for juniors, ask why.</p>

<h3 id="key-takeaway-2">Key Takeaway</h3>
<blockquote>
  <p>Your first role sets the trajectory for your career. A supportive, growth-focused environment will accelerate your development. A toxic or unsupportive role will crush your confidence. Choose wisely‚Äîit‚Äôs okay to be selective.</p>
