<h3 id="dealing-with-rejection">Dealing with Rejection</h3>

<p><strong>You will get rejected. A lot.</strong></p>

<p><strong>Types of rejection:</strong></p>
<ul>
  <li>Silent ghosting (the worst)</li>
  <li>Automated ‚Äúthanks but no thanks‚Äù</li>
  <li>‚ÄúYou were great but we went with someone else‚Äù</li>
  <li>‚ÄúYou‚Äôre not senior enough‚Äù (for a junior role)</li>
</ul>

<p><strong>How to handle it:</strong></p>

<p><strong>1. Remember: It‚Äôs not personal</strong>
Most rejections are about fit, timing, or budget‚Äînot your worth.</p>

<p><strong>2. Ask for feedback when possible</strong>
Some companies will tell you why. Most won‚Äôt. Ask anyway.</p>

<p><strong>3. Learn what you can</strong>
If you‚Äôre consistently struggling in interviews, identify the pattern and address it.</p>

<p><strong>4. Celebrate the practice</strong>
Each interview is practice. You‚Äôre getting better every time.</p>

<h3 id="key-takeaway-3">Key Takeaway</h3>
<blockquote>
  <p>The job search will test you. It‚Äôs designed to. The ones who make it aren‚Äôt necessarily the most talented‚Äîthey‚Äôre the most persistent. Keep going. Every ‚Äúno‚Äù gets you closer to the ‚Äúyes‚Äù that matters.</p>
